  "prompt": "Is Hinduism monotheistic or polytheistic?",
  "response": "Hinduism is a complex and diverse tradition, and whether it is considered monotheistic or polytheistic depends on how one interprets its teachings and practices. It can be viewed through both lenses, and it also transcends these categories in some interpretations.\n\n1. **Polytheistic Perspective**:  \n   Hinduism is often described as polytheistic because it includes a vast pantheon of deities, each representing different aspects of the divine, natural forces, or human experiences. Deities like Vishnu, Shiva, Lakshmi, and Durga are worshipped individually, and rituals and prayers are often directed to specific gods and goddesses.\n\n2. **Monotheistic Perspective**:  \n   At the same time, Hinduism can be seen as monotheistic in the sense that many Hindus believe in a single, ultimate reality or supreme being (Brahman) that manifests in various forms (deities). This philosophy is expressed in texts like the Upanishads, which describe Brahman as the unchanging, infinite, and formless reality underlying all existence. The many gods and goddesses are often interpreted as different manifestations or aspects of this one supreme reality.\n\n3. **Henotheistic or Monistic Perspectives**:  \n   Hinduism is sometimes described as henotheistic, meaning the worship of one primary deity while acknowledging the existence of others. Additionally, the Advaita Vedanta school of Hindu philosophy emphasizes monism, the idea that all existence is ultimately one, and the apparent diversity of gods and forms is an illusion (maya).\n\nIn summary, Hinduism is flexible and accommodates a wide range of beliefs and practices, allowing individuals to approach the divine in ways that resonate with them. It can be seen as polytheistic, monotheistic, or even monistic, depending on the context and the philosophical framework one adopts.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
